Matching Pennies

  • There is no Nash Equilibirum in pure strategies

    • Not to be confused with subgame-perfect Nash Equilibria (SPNE), we may refer to pure strategy Nash Equilibria as PSNE

  • What do we do?

    1. Assume Bean is playing a mixed strategy

      • Compute Seanâs expected payoffs in response to Bean

      • Use these to find when Sean could be induced to play a mixed strategy

    2. Assume Sean is playing a mixed strategy

      • Compute Beanâs expected payoffs in response to Sean

      • Use these to find when Bean could be induced to play a mixed strategy

    • When both players play (mixed) strategies that induce the other player to mix, we called this our MSNE

Example 1: BoS

Letâs find all NE in BoS

  • First things first: check for PSNE

    • (R,R) and (F,F) are NE
  • Step 1-0
  • 1-1
  • Step 2-0
  • 2-1

  • Suppose player 2 is playing \(\tau=qR+(1-q)F\)

    • \(E[u_1(R, \tau)] = 3q+(1-q)=1+2q\)

    • \(E[u_1(F, \tau)] = 0+2(1-q)=2-2q\)

  • Player 1 mixes when these expected payoffs are equal

\[\begin{align*} E[u_1(R, \tau)]&=E[u_1(F, \tau)]\\ 1+2q&=2-2q\\ 4q&=1\\ q&=\frac{1}{4} \end{align*}\]

  • Player 1 mixes when \(q=1/4\), ie when player 2 is playing \(\frac{1}{4}R+\frac{3}{4}F\)

  • Suppose player 1 is playing \(\sigma=pR+(1-p)F\)

    • \(E[u_2(\sigma, R)] = 2p\)

    • \(E[u_2(\sigma, F)] = p+3(1-p)=3-2p\)

  • Player 2 mixes when these expected payoffs are equal

\[\begin{align*} E[u_2(\sigma, R)] &=E[u_2(\sigma, F)]\\ 2p&=3-2p\\ 4p&=3\\ p&=\frac{3}{4} \end{align*}\]

  • Player 2 mixes when \(q=3/4\), ie when player 1 is playing \(\frac{3}{4}R+\frac{1}{4}F\)

Example 1: BoS (cont.)

  • When player 1 is playing \(\sigma(3/4)=(3/4)R+(1/4)F\), player 2 is indifferent between their pure strategies, so they can be induced to mix

  • When player 2 is playing \(\tau(1/4)=(1/4)R+(3/4)F\), player 1 is indifferent between their pure strategies, so they can be induced to mix

  • So, when players are playing \(\{\sigma(3/4), \tau(1/4)\}\), both players are indifferent between any other strategies they could play

    • In other words, no one can deviate for strictly higher payoffs

  • Hence, \[\{\sigma(3/4), \tau(1/4)\}\] is our MSNE

Fun fact: an Oddity

  • We already know that some form of NE exists in every normal-form game

  • How many exist?

  • A fun, wild theorem was proven in the â80s: if you populate a normal form game of any size with random values, the probability of getting a game with an odd number of NE is 1

    • Note: that doesnât actually mean always, it just means itâs very unlikely that you get a game with an even # of equilibria

Visualizing MSNE

  • Visualizing mixed strategies will give us a lot of information about our game in question

  • There are two types of graphs which we are interested in drawing:

    1. Expected payoff graph

    2. Best response plot

  • We will focus on first one today

Expected Payoff Graph

  • Suppose opponent is playing a mixed strategy involving only two pure strategies

    • ex: \(\tau(q)=qX+(1-q) Y\)

  • Idea: graph the expected payoff of playing each of oneâs pure strategies in response to this mixed strategy against the probability parameter

    • e.g.Â plot \(E[u_i(s, \tau)]\) on the y-axis, and \(q\) on the x-axis.

  • Ex: For BoS, we found

    • \(E[u_1(R, \tau)] = 1+2q\)

    • \(E[u_1(F, \tau)] = 2-2q\)

  • So, letâs plot each of these against \(q\)

    • Note: letâs de-clutter some notation:
      • we know we are taking expected values
      • we know the opponent is playing a mixed strategy, and the name isnât all too important

Expected Payoff Graph for BoS

Player 1âs expected payoff from playing â¦

  • \(R\) in response to \(\tau\) is \(u_1(R) = 1+2q\)
  • \(F\) in response to \(\tau\) is \(u_1(F) = 2-2q\)

BR from a graph

  • Where the lines intersect = where player 1 is indifferent between playing \(R\) and playing \(F\)

    • This is exactly \(q=0.25\), like we found

  • What else?

  • What happens when \(q\neq0.25\)?

    • When \(q<0.25\), the payoff of playing \(F\) exceeds that of playing \(R\)

    • When \(q>0.25\), the payoff of playing \(R\) exceeds that of playing \(F\)

  • With this info, we can now build player 1âs Best Response as a function of \(q\): \[ BR_1(q)= \begin{cases} F & q<0.25\\ \{R,F\} & q=0.25\\ R & q>0.25 \end{cases} \]

Sketching E.P. Graphs

Sketching E.P. Graphs

  • Itâs easier than you think to sketch one of these from a game table

  • Read from bottom to top, the payoffs for each strategy match the left-to-right values on the graph

Another Example

  • Similarly: For player 1, the payoffs for each strategy, read from right to left, match the left-to-right values on the graph

Why?

  • Our arbitrary mixed strategies simply mimic the definition of a line

  • For starting point \(p_1\) to end point \(p_2\), a line can be parameterized according to \[tp_1 + (1-t)p_2\] for \(t\in[0,1]\)

  • Our mixed strategies are just linear combinations of pure strategies, but I digress

  • The fact that we have to read the tables âbackwardsâ is because we put \(q\) on the âfirstâ strategy1

  1. For this reason, some authors choose to denote mixed strategies as \((1-q)X+qY\)

More info from E.P. Graphs

Best response

  • We already saw one connection between the the expected payoff graph for a player and the playerâs BR function

  • As it turns out, the entirety of a playerâs best response function is baked into this graph

    • For a given \(q\) value, we can trace up to the highest line on the expected payoff graph at the point \(q\): this is our best response!

The Upper Envelope

  • Whatâs more: focus on the highest lines for any given \(q\) value, and stitch these together

  • This generates what is called the Upper Envelope for a graph, and letâs us get direct information on the best response function

  • Ex: Consider the following expected payoff graph

    • Assume itâs for some player with access to strategies \(X\), \(Y\), and \(Z\)

    • In response to a strategy of the form \(\sigma=pA+(1-p)B\)

Using the Upper Envelope to get a BR function

  • Upper Envelope
  • BR function

\[BR_2(p)= \begin{cases} X & p < p_1^*\\ {X, Y} & p = p_1^*\\ Y & p \in p_1^*\le p \le p_2^*\\ {Y, Z} & p = p_2^*\\ Z & p=p_2^* \end{cases} \]

Recall

  • At the end of week 3 (slide deck 6), we saw the following information
  • Sd-6

  • Def [Version 1.0]: A (pure) strategy \(\tilde{s}\in S_{i}\) is said to be Never a Best Response provided that \(\tilde{s}\notin BR_{i}(s_{-i})\) for any \(s_{-i}\in S_{-i}\)

  • How is this related to strict/weak domination?

  • Fact: a strictly dominated strategy is never a best response

    • Why?

  • Do we want to eliminate NBRs a la IDSDS?

    • No, at least not using this definition
    • We will return to this later, when we resume mixed strategies
  • Now, itâs later

Updated Definition

  • Def [Version 2.0]: A strategy is said to be Never a Best Response provided that it is never a component of a playerâs best response function â taking into account mixed strategies

    • In other words, a strategy is an NBR provided that it isnât in the upper envelope of an agentâs expected payoff graph

  • For the updated definition, I will also use NBR interchangeably with non-rationalizable

    • We could say an agentâs strategy is rationalizable if it is in the upper envelope (/ is a component of the agentâs best response function)

The importance of rationalizability

  • With this updated definition, we actually can eliminate NBRs iteratively â preserving all of the properties of IDSDS

    • However, since we are now in mixed strategy world, it is often not practical to do so

  • In fact, eliminating NBRâs in this manner is equivalent to iteratively eliminating strictly dominated strategies

    • NBR \(\implies\) strictly dominated. The strategy may be dominated by a mixed strategy

  • Once again: the expected payoff graphs give us a lot of information
